f sanctions.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL5221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833600","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-13","<p>​The Zimbabwe Government recognised their legal obligation to pay for pensions of former Southern Rhodesia civil servants in a letter from the Minister of Public Service, Labour and Social Welfare on 28 October 2016. Representatives from the British High Commission in Harare regularly raise the requirement of the Government of Zimbabwe to pay these pensions with the Zimbabwean government and will continue to do so.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-02-13T15:32:47.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833600/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833600/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Zimbabwe: Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the most recent outcome of discussions with the government of Zimbabwe about pension payments owing to former Southern Rhodesia civil servants.","false","Biography information for Lord Goodlad",,"Lord Goodlad","HL5222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833601","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-13","<p>The Minister of State for Asia and the Pacific, Mark Field, responded to a letter on this subject from the Hong Kong Police Association on 30 January 2018. That letter confirmed that we have no record that any assurances were given concerning present or future visa or nationality requirements for former or retired Royal Hong Kong Police officers, and their spouses, partners or children. In that context, any visa applications will be considered against the current legal framework in place in the UK.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-02-13T17:05:17.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833601/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833601/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Hong Kong: Visas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what progress has been made in fulfilling the assurances about parity with crown servants in the UK given to overseas civil servants in Hong Kong, following enquiries by the Hong Kong Policy Association about the visa process for partners of officers who served in the Royal Hong Kong police.","false","Biography information for Lord Goodlad",,"Lord Goodlad","HL5223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833602","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-13","<p>The Foreign Secretary met with the Environment Secretary, scientists and representatives of environmental non-governmental organisations on 29 January to discuss options for future protective measures around South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands. No final decision has been made whilst consideration is given to the consequences of the options available. An announcement will be made in due course.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-02-13T15:28:38.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833602/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833602/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","South Georgia and South Sandwich Islands: Environment Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they intend to announce the conclusions to the consultation process about extending marine protection measures around South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands; and whether further legislation is required to bring about any such protections.","false","Biography information for Lord Haworth",,"Lord Haworth","HL5224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833604","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-08","<p>We understand that the British Thyroid Association (BTA) advises that a small proportion of patients treated with the most commonly used drug, levothyroxine, continue to suffer with symptoms despite adequate biochemical correction. In these circumstances, where levothyroxine has failed and in line with BTA guidance, endocrinologists providing NHS services may recommend liothyronine for individual patients after a carefully audited trial of at least three months’ duration of liothyronine.</p><p>NHS England’s recommendations to clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) take account of those of the BTA and are to:</p><p>- Advise CCGs that prescribers in primary care should not initiate liothyronine for any new patient;</p><p> </p><p>- Advise CCGs that individuals currently prescribed liothyronine should be reviewed by a consultant NHS endocrinologist with consideration given to switching to levothyroxine where clinically appropriate; and</p><p> </p><p>- Advise CCGs that a local decision, involving the Area Prescribing Committee (or equivalent) informed by national guidance (e.g. from the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence or the Regional Medicines Optimisation Committee), should be made regarding arrangements for on-going prescribing of liothyronine. This should be for individuals who, in exceptional circumstances, have an on-going need for liothyronine as confirmed by a consultant National Health Service endocrinologist.</p><p>A number of CCGs had already created local policies on the prescribing of liothryronine before the national consultation started in July 2017.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL5228","2018-02-08T15:03:07.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833604/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833604/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Thyroid Diseases: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the extent to which the NHS England document Items which should not be routinely prescribed in primary care: Guidance for CCGs reflects the most recent view of the British Thyroid Association.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL5225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833605","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-08","<p>We understand that whilst it is recognised that some patients on levothyroxine remain symptomatic despite treatment leading to thyroid stimulating hormone levels in the therapeutic range, it is not possible to predict the number as the reasons for this are not fully understood; such patients should be under the care of an endocrinologist. Where clinical commissioning groups decide to implement recommendations in NHS England’s guidance, they are responsible for deciding whether further action is required, such as commissioning research, to monitor uptake and outcomes.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL5291","2018-02-08T15:11:47.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833605/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833605/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Levothyroxine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what proportion of patients treated with levothyroxine continue to suffer with symptoms despite adequate biochemical correction.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL5226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833606","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-09","<p>NHS England have sought advice from the leading clinical experts in this field. These are the Royal College of Physicians, the British Thyroid Association and the European Thyroid Association. These experts recommend that, for the vast majority of patients, levothyroxine alone is used in the treatment of hypothyroidism. They also advise that liothyronine should be considered in exceptional circumstances.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-02-09T12:00:40.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833606/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833606/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Liothyronine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have evidence showing that there are more cost-effective products available than liothyronine for the treatment of thyroid disease; and if so, whether they will publish that evidence.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL5227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833608","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-08","<p>We understand that the British Thyroid Association (BTA) advises that a small proportion of patients treated with the most commonly used drug, levothyroxine, continue to suffer with symptoms despite adequate biochemical correction. In these circumstances, where levothyroxine has failed and in line with BTA guidance, endocrinologists providing NHS services may recommend liothyronine for individual patients after a carefully audited trial of at least three months’ duration of liothyronine.</p><p>NHS England’s recommendations to clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) take account of those of the BTA and are to:</p><p>- Advise CCGs that prescribers in primary care should not initiate liothyronine for any new patient;</p><p> </p><p>- Advise CCGs that individuals currently prescribed liothyronine should be reviewed by a consultant NHS endocrinologist with consideration given to switching to levothyroxine where clinically appropriate; and</p><p> </p><p>- Advise CCGs that a local decision, involving the Area Prescribing Committee (or equivalent) informed by national guidance (e.g. from the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence or the Regional Medicines Optimisation Committee), should be made regarding arrangements for on-going prescribing of liothyronine. This should be for individuals who, in exceptional circumstances, have an on-going need for liothyronine as confirmed by a consultant National Health Service endocrinologist.</p><p>A number of CCGs had already created local policies on the prescribing of liothryronine before the national consultation started in July 2017.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL5225","2018-02-08T15:03:07.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833608/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833608/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Liothyronine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether any Clinical Commissioning Groups refused to allow patients to be prescribed liothyronine (T3) before the consultation on Items which should not be routinely prescribed in primary care: Guidance for CCGs commenced; and if so, why.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL5228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833609","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-08","<p>We have made no such estimate. However NHS England expects local clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) – who have responsibility for commissioning these services - to have regard to the guidance when determining their local prescribing decisions. As such, it will be for local CCGs, in conjunction with local providers to determine what is best for patients and as part of their decision making, the resources available to implement any change.</p><p>The Regional Medicines Optimisation Committee (South) has considered this issue in further detail and a statement will be issued by them in due course to support CCGs and secondary care providers in reviewing patients, in line with the recommendations made. Regional Medicines Optimisation Committees make recommendations, provide resources and co-ordinate activities to ensure the optimal use of medicines for the benefit of patients and the National Health Service.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-02-08T15:12:56.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833609/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833609/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Liothyronine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made of (1) the additional workload, and (2) the added cost for secondary care providers resulting from the decisions that (a) individuals currently prescribed liothyronine should be reviewed by a consultant NHS endocrinologist with consideration given to switching to levothyroxine where clinically appropriate, and (b) individual patients with an ongoing need for liothyronine should have that confirmed by a consultant NHS endocrinologist.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL5229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833610","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-07","<p>My Department has made clear that it considers that building owners are responsible for funding fire safety measures including replacement of dangerous cladding. Government will consider financial flexibilities for local authorities who need to undertake essential fire safety work to make a building safe. Housing associations that are concerned about their ability to meet these costs should contact the social housing regulator.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-02-07T13:15:02.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833610/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833610/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-30","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan to use the HM Treasury central contingencies fund to meet the costs of removing and replacing dangerous cladding on tower blocks in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833611","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-13","<p>The former Minister for Africa, Rory Stewart MP, raised the importance of timely elections with President Kabila when he visited Kinshasa in November. The British Government has repeatedly called for President Kabila to honour both the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) Constitution and the 31 December agreement and conduct a peaceful transfer of power in DRC via credible elections. The UK, alongside regional and international partners, will continue to press the DRC authorities to adhere to their electoral commitment.</p><p>In a statement on 3 January, following the deaths of protestors on 31 December 2017, we called on the government to investigate and hold accountable security force members who fired on civilians or ordered the use of lethal force.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-02-13T15:27:21.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833611/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833611/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Democratic Republic of Congo: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo regarding President Kabila remaining in office more than a year after the expiration of his constitutional term; and whether they have any plans to call for an independent inquiry into the deaths and injuries arising out of the peaceful anti-Kabila protests on 31 December 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833612","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-12","<p>The events of 15 January are a worrying development as the human rights situation continues to deteriorate rapidly in Venezuela. Law enforcement officers have a right to protect themselves using proportionate force. We urge the Venezuelan Government to ensure that the actions of law enforcement officers are measured, proportionate, and in accordance with the rule of law.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-02-12T16:12:48.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833612/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833612/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Venezuela: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the human rights implications of the police action in Venezuela that killed nine people on 15 January.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833613","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-13","<p>​We have been in ongoing dialogue with the Western Cape provincial and Cape Town municipal governments on the current water scarcity issues they face. The International Trade Secretary discussed the situation with the Western Cape government in Cape Town on 18 September 2017. Exchanges with UK experts have since followed both in London and in Cape Town to explore how UK expertise could help address the short and long term water challenges.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-02-13T17:00:56.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833613/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833613/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","South Africa: Water Supply","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have any plans to enter into discussions with, and to offer assistance to, the government of South Africa concerning the water supply crisis in Cape Town.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones",,"Lord Jones","HL5233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833614","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-06","<p>Yes.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2018-02-06T17:06:58.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833614/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833614/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Future Strategic Tanker Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the Future Strategic Tanker Aircraft contracts include provisions to allow all aircraft covered by those contracts to be part of the core fleet.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL5234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833615","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-06","<p>The service and maintenance records of Royal Navy warships, submarines and the majority of the Royal Fleet Auxiliary's ships are held centrally and electronically, and kept for up to 10 years.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL5236","2018-02-06T15:57:12.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833615/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833615/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Warships: Repairs and Maintenance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to centralise and computerise HM ships maintenance records, which are currently held in documents on board ships.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL5235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833617","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-06","<p>The service and maintenance records of Royal Navy warships, submarines and the majority of the Royal Fleet Auxiliary's ships are held centrally and electronically, and kept for up to 10 years.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL5235","2018-02-06T15:57:12.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833617/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833617/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Warships: Repairs and Maintenance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the current retention period for data on the maintenance of HM ships.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL5236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833618","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-06","<p>Support for all F-35 aircraft is being developed and established by the US-based F-35 Joint Program Office, through the Global Support Solution. This will service all F-35 partner nations, including the UK. Support contracts will therefore be denominated in US dollars.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2018-02-06T15:55:55.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833618/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833618/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government in what currencies support contracts for the F35B aircraft will be denominated.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL5237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833619","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-06","<p>Initial support for the P-8A Poseidon aircraft will be provided in the USA as part of the foreign military sale arrangement with the US Government.</p><p>As preparations are still at an early stage, and commercial negotiations have not yet taken place, it is not possible to provide any further details including the likely location of support work, or the currency of the contracts.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2018-02-06T17:08:36.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833619/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833619/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government where major support work for the P-8A Poseidon aircraft will be carried out; and in what currency the contracts will be denominated.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL5238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833620","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-06","<p>An initial two-year support package for the AH-64E helicopter will be provided by the US Government as part of the foreign military sales agreement through which the helicopters will be supplied. This will be denominated in US dollars.</p><p>The invitation to negotiate for long-term training and support, beyond the initial package, was issued to Boeing Defence UK in December 2017. We do not expect to place the contract until 2020 and a decision on the currency denomination will form part of the negotiation process.</p><p>No decision has yet been made on the location of the support work.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2018-02-06T15:56:34.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833620/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833620/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Apache AH-64 Helicopters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government where major support work for the AH-64E helicopters will be carried out; and in what currency the contracts will be denominated.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL5239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833621","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-12","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) recognises that developments in this field are moving quickly and in January 2018, the specific reference to “blood glucose monitoring” was removed from the relevant regulations. This will potentially allow alternative methods of glucose monitoring to be accommodated in the future if it is deemed appropriate by expert medical opinion in the context of driving and maintaining road safety.</p><p>The DVLA is working closely with the Secretary of State for Transport’s Honorary Medical Advisory Panel on driving and diabetes mellitus to understand the potential impacts of allowing the use of alternative methods of glucose monitoring. This issue was discussed at the panel’s October meeting. The panel feels that there is currently insufficient evidence about the use of flash glucose monitoring devices in the context of driving to ensure road safety standards are maintained. The panel will continue to consider further evidence as it emerges.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-02-12T13:36:53.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833621/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833621/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-30","Driving: Diabetes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what consideration has been given to amending the DVLA guidance for persons with diabetes to allow for those who use flash glucose monitoring and any other new technology to measure glucose levels.","false","Biography information for Lord Morris of Aberavon",,"Lord Morris of Aberavon","HL5240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833622","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-08","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) report <em>The Rise in the use of the MHA to detain people in England</em>, published on 22 January 2018, identified a number of issues which may have contributed to the rise in detentions under the Mental Health Act 1983.</p><p>These issues include changes in mental health service provision and bed management, and the fact that patients may be admitted more frequently than before, either as part of a plan of care or because of premature discharge. The report also acknowledged that demographic and social changes have resulted in an increase in the size of population that is at risk of detention.</p><p>A copy of the CQC’s report is attached.</p><p>The Government is aware that rates of detention under the Mental Health Act 1983 have been rising and welcomes the CQC’s report. The report acknowledges that the Government is improving services and that these may help to reverse the increases in detentions under the Act, pointing to NHS England’s national access standard for Early Intervention in Psychosis services and the £400 million dedicated as part of the Five Year Forward View for Mental health to enhance crisis resolution home treatment teams.</p><p>The rise in detentions under the Act is one of the reasons the Government has commissioned an Independent Review of the Mental Health Act. The Review, chaired by Professor Sir Simon Wessely, has been tasked with reviewing issues around the legislation itself and the practice surrounding it, and it will make its recommendations to Government in autumn 2018.</p><p>The CQC is one of a number of organisations working closely with the Independent Review and its report was produced with the expectation that it be considered by the Review.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-02-08T15:10:57.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833622/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833622/answer","HL5241 CQC Report The Rise in the use of the MHA to detain people in England.pdf","HL5241 CQC Report The Rise in the use of the MHA to detain people in England.pdf","The Rise in the use of the MHA to detain people","The Rise in the use of the MHA to detain people","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833622/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Mental Health Services: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of (1) failings in the mental health system, (2) the identified causes of such failings, and (3) remedial actions proposed by the Care Quality Commission, especially to reduce the number of detentions made under the Mental Health Act 2007.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL5241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833624","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-08","<p>The non-statutory sector plays a vital role in supporting children with mental health needs, including those in vulnerable families. To support local leadership and accountability for local transformation, Future in Mind introduced cross-agency Local Transformation Plans for children and young people’s mental health services. These now form part of local Sustainability and Transformation Plans and provide a basis for local areas to work with commissioners and providers across health, social care, education, youth justice and the voluntary sector, bringing everyone together to plan strategically, reflecting the needs of local communities. All plans must provide evidence of effective joint working with the voluntary sector.</p><p>This programme is supported by an additional £1.4 billion available from 2015/16 to 2019/20 to transform children and young people’s mental health services. NHS England’s 2016 survey <em>Children and young people’s mental health Local Transformation Plans – a summary of key themes</em>, includes many examples of work with the voluntary sector. A copy is attached.</p><p>The Government is aware that more needs to be done to support children with mental health from vulnerable families. The Green Paper, <em>Transforming Children and Young People’s Mental Health Provision</em>, published last year, includes proposals to improve early intervention through Mental Health Support Teams linked to schools. We are consulting on the approach to implementing these proposals, including how they can best support vulnerable groups. The Green Paper also includes a commitment to commission research on how to engage vulnerable families, to provide information to local areas when referring children and parents to both parenting and parental conflict interventions. A copy of the Green Paper is attached.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-02-08T15:05:36.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833624/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833624/answer","cyp-mh-ltp.pdf ; Transforming_children_and_young_people_s_mental_health_provision.pdf","cyp-mh-ltp.pdf ; Transforming_children_and_young_people_s_mental_health_provision.pdf","Children and young people's mental health ; Green Paper","Children and young people's mental health ; Green Paper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833624/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what consideration they have given to the preventative work done by the non-statutory sector in providing support to children and young people with mental health illnesses in vulnerable families; and what assessment they have made of how such provision can be boosted with additional resources to complement and enhance the work undertaken by health care professional staff.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL5242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833625","Home Office","false","2018-02-06","<p>Six PCCs have submitted proposals to take on governance of local fire and rescue services (Northamptonshire, Hertfordshire, Staffordshire, West Mercia, Cambridgeshire and North Yorkshire). Five of these did not have agreement from the relevant local authorities and so in November 2017 the Secretary of State commissioned independent assessments of the proposals in accordance with the legislation. <br>These assessments have now been received and decisions will be announced in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-02-06T17:16:29.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833625/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833625/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-30","Police and Crime Commissioners: Fire and Rescue Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they expect a decision to be made on the proposals by five police and crime commissioners to take on the functions of fire and rescue authorities under the Policing and Crime Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL5243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833626","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-02-08","<p>Government's strategy Sporting Future is clear that everyone should have the opportunity to engage in sport and physical activity and to enjoy the benefits that this brings.</p><p> </p><p>Many sports, including darts, have a huge potential to deliver a range of positive outcomes including physical and mental wellbeing as well as individual and community development.</p><p> </p><p>The most recently published Active Lives survey shows that 8,800 people in England regularly play darts.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2018-02-08T16:32:21.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833626/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833626/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-30","Darts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the cultural and educational value of the sport of dart playing.","false","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL5244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833627","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","true","2018-02-06","<p><del class="ministerial">Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) spent £3.8m on invasive non-native species in 2016/17 including both direct costs and apportioned support staff and overheads.</del></p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial">APHA do not keep the split as requested but can further subdivide the cost between direct costs (£2.2m) and apportioned support staff and overheads (£1.6m).</del></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">Biosecurity and control of invasive non-native species are devolved matters.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">In England in 2016/17 the government spent an estimated total of £922,000 on biosecurity measures relating to invasive non-native species.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The overall cost can be apportioned as £145,000 for policy functions, £90,000 on risk analysis, £335,000 for early warning and rapid response measures, £210,000 on coordination, £80,000 on communication and awareness raising activities, and £62,000 on research.</ins></p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-02-06T13:51:04.393Z","2018-02-21T18:49:37.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833627/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833627/answer",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833627/answer/previousversion/39616","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-30","Non-native Species","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much they spent in the 2016–17 financial year on biosecurity measures relating to invasive non-native species, broken down by (1) policy functions, (2) inspectorate functions, (3) technical support functions, for example, risk assessments and diagnostics, (4) response functions, including control activities, and (5) research.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL5245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833629","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-06","<p>Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) spent £13.2m on plant and tree diseases in 2016/17 including both direct costs and apportioned support staff and overheads.</p><p> </p><p>APHA do not keep the split as requested but can further subdivide the cost between direct costs (£10.1m) and apportioned support staff and overheads (£3.1m).</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-02-06T13:51:33.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833629/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833629/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-30","Plants: Disease Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much they spent in the 2016–17 financial year on biosecurity measures relating to plant diseases and pests, broken down by (1) policy functions, (2) inspectorate functions, (3) technical support functions, for example, risk assessments and diagnostics, (4) response functions, including control activities, and (5) research.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL5246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833630","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-06","<p>Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) spent £13.2m on plant and tree diseases in 2016/17 including both direct costs and apportioned support staff and overheads.</p><p> </p><p>APHA do not keep the split as requested but can further subdivide the cost between direct costs (£10.1m) and apportioned support staff and overheads (£3.1m).</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-02-06T14:59:47.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833630/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833630/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-30","Trees: Disease Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much they spent in the 2016–17 financial year on biosecurity measures relating to tree diseases and pests, broken down by (1) policy functions, (2) inspectorate functions, (3) technical support functions, for example, risk assessments and diagnostics, (4) response functions, including control activities, and (5) research.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL5247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833631","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-13","<p>Data on all these matters are not held centrally. Collation of this information would involve analysts across different organisations (Defra, APHA, Environment Agency, Fera and the Forestry Commission) analysing and collating data stored in different formats for a wide range of pests and diseases. As a result, we are not able to provide the information within the given timeframe.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-02-13T16:18:58.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833631/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833631/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-30","Animals and Plants: Diseases","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their estimate of the annual cost to the English economy from (1) animal diseases, (2) bee diseases, (3) fish diseases, (4) invasive non-native species, (5) plant diseases, and (6) tree diseases.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL5248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833632","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-06","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2018-02-06T17:11:34.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833632/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833632/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Army: Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many panel display screens have been purchased for army vehicles in the last five years; and at what cost.","false","Biography information for Lord Robathan",,"Lord Robathan","HL5249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833633","Cabinet Office","false","2018-02-08","<p>The Government has made no specific assessment of this. The EU referendum was a democratic exercise, run under the rules on campaigning as set out in the European Union Referendum Act 2015. The Government believes that the result of the referendum should be respected and delivered.</p><p>The Government recognises the problems caused by misleading and false information online more broadly, and we take the security and integrity of our democratic processes very seriously.</p><p>The Government’s manifesto includes a commitment to take steps to protect the reliability and objectivity of information that is essential to our democracy and a free, independent press. Therefore we are working with the broadcast and press sectors, social media and the broader tech industry, academics and international partner governments to ensure we have a news environment where accurate content can prevail. We are also working to improve the critical analysis and digital literacy skills of the wider population.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2018-02-08T17:01:29.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833633/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833633/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-30","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of whether incorrect information on social media influenced the outcome of the referendum on the UK's membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL5250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833635","Home Office","false","2018-02-09","<p>There are currently no plans to record the numbers of asylum seekers who require treatment for mental illness. Although every opportunity is afforded to asylum seekers to disclose this information during the process, there is no obligation on their part to do so</p><p>The staff working with asylum seekers are trained to identify mental health concerns but are not medically trained to identify the need for treatment. Where mental health concern is identified, the asylum seeker is referred or signposted to medical or support services.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-02-09T11:59:30.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833635/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833635/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-30","Asylum: Mental Illness","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 29 January (HL5401), whether they are considering recording the number of asylum seekers who require treatment for mental illness.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL5251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833636","Home Office","false","2018-02-09","<p>Asylum seekers and their dependents who would otherwise be destitute are provided with a weekly cash allowance and free accommodation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-02-09T12:39:20.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833636/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833636/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-30","Asylum: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what aid is available for destitute asylum seekers who are not allowed to work and are not entitled to benefits.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL5252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833637","Home Office","false","2018-02-06","<p>In order to publicise the replacement of the Azure card we wrote to all service users informing them of the change, and what the implications were for them. We briefed service providers and the voluntary sector about the forthcoming change to ensure that advice and guidance was available in case of difficulty.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-02-06T17:03:43.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833637/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833637/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-30","Asylum: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how the replacement of the Azure card by the Aspen card for asylum seekers was publicised.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL5253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833638","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-06","<p>The UK is providing essential medical care to vulnerable migrants and refugees on their journeys towards Europe and beyond. By the end of 2016 for example, UK aid had supported over 300,000 first aid interventions and medical consultations as part of the Mediterranean migration crisis response. We have also been at the forefront of medical relief provision to displaced people in areas affected by conflict. For instance, the UK has helped provide over 10.3 million medical consultations and over 8.3 million vaccines across Syria and the region since 2012.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has also welcomed over 9,300 refugees under the Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme since it began in 2014. All refugees that are referred by the UN High Commissioner for Refugees for potential resettlement undergo a Health Assessment in the region. Details are passed to receiving local authorities so they can ensure that suitable treatment can be provided upon arrival.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-02-06T17:26:48.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833638/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833638/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-30","Asylum: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what provision they have made for essential medication to be available to displaced people on their migration journey before they arrive in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL5254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833639","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-07","<p>Effective scrutiny of elected city region mayors is essential for ensuring that these mayors are that single point of accountability which underpins the devolution deals Government has entered in to with those city regions. Mayoral combined authorities are subject to the local authority accountability, audit and propriety regimes which we have strengthened by the Combined Authorities (Overview and Scrutiny Committees, Access to Information and Audit Committees) Order 2017, which Parliament has approved and which we developed with assistance from the Centre for Public Scrutiny and the National Audit Office. This Order makes special provisions about the establishment and operation of overview and scrutiny committees and audit committees in order that mayors, who are required to appear before an overview and scrutiny committee when requested, can robustly be held to account.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-02-07T13:16:31.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833639/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833639/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-30","Mayors","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what checks and balances they have put in place to ensure that the actions of elected city mayors are subject to proper and impartial scrutiny.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833641","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-06","<p>The joint agreement reached in December, which confirmed a shared desire to make progress on an implementation period; and that sufficient progress had been made to progress to phase two of negotiations for exiting the EU, was widely welcomed by businesses and has helped business optimism.</p><p> </p><p>Business optimism is also driven by confidence in the long-term performance of the economy. The Industrial Strategy, published by my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy last year, sets out a long-term vision of an economy that boosts productivity and earning power throughout the UK.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-02-06T13:48:05.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833641/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833641/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to address reports of falling confidence amongst business leaders with regard to Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL5256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833642","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The UK Government is considering the report of the European Union Committee on Brexit and energy security published on 29 January and will respond shortly.</p><p>The Government is currently considering all aspects of its future relationship with the EU, including in energy. Our priority is to maintain affordable, clean and secure energy supplies for businesses and households.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-02-05T17:07:22.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833642/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833642/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Energy: UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to diminish the impact of Brexit on energy trading following the report of the European Union Committee, Brexit: energy security (HL Paper 63, 10th Report, 2017–19) published on 29 January.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL5257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833643","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-08","<p>As with any vocation, personnel leave the Armed Forces for a variety of reasons. Exit interviews are conducted at a unit level but are not routinely collated centrally. As part of the leaving process, soldiers complete a short survey. Within the Royal Logistic Corps, 2016/17 survey responses indicate that the primary reasons for leaving included seeking fresh challenges, opportunities outside of the Army, personal circumstances, and job satisfaction.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2018-02-08T16:31:49.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833643/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833643/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Royal Logistics Corps","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the principal response from soldiers leaving the Royal Logistics Corps in exit interviews.","false","Biography information for Lord Temple-Morris",,"Lord Temple-Morris","HL5258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833644","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Global Challenges Research Fund (GCRF) mainly supports projects where the benefits are to multiple countries. In 2016, the latest date for which figures are available, 92.4% of GCRF spend was reported as non-country specific ODA spend with no single benefitting country. Of the remaining 7.6%, the highest spend was assigned to regional projects in Africa and to Tanzania, Cote D’Ivoire, South Africa, Guatemala and Peru.</p><p>In 2016, 12% of GCRF spend was categorised as “Medical Research”, we do not hold data on subcategories within this area.</p>",,"Lord Henley","HL5260 ; HL5261","2018-02-05T17:08:16.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833644/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833644/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Global Challenges Research Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what proportion of the Global Challenges Research Fund is spent on (1) family planning, (2) sexual and reproductive health and rights, and (3) population issues, in the developing world.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833646","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Global Challenges Research Fund (GCRF) mainly supports projects where the benefits are to multiple countries. In 2016, the latest date for which figures are available, 92.4% of GCRF spend was reported as non-country specific ODA spend with no single benefitting country. Of the remaining 7.6%, the highest spend was assigned to regional projects in Africa and to Tanzania, Cote D’Ivoire, South Africa, Guatemala and Peru.</p><p>In 2016, 12% of GCRF spend was categorised as “Medical Research”, we do not hold data on subcategories within this area.</p>",,"Lord Henley","HL5259 ; HL5261","2018-02-05T17:08:16.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833646/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833646/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Global Challenges Research Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what countries receive Official Development Assistance through the Global Challenges Research Fund.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833647","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Global Challenges Research Fund (GCRF) mainly supports projects where the benefits are to multiple countries. In 2016, the latest date for which figures are available, 92.4% of GCRF spend was reported as non-country specific ODA spend with no single benefitting country. Of the remaining 7.6%, the highest spend was assigned to regional projects in Africa and to Tanzania, Cote D’Ivoire, South Africa, Guatemala and Peru.</p><p>In 2016, 12% of GCRF spend was categorised as “Medical Research”, we do not hold data on subcategories within this area.</p>",,"Lord Henley","HL5259 ; HL5260","2018-02-05T17:08:16.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833647/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833647/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Health Services: Developing Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what proportion of the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy budget is spent on (1) family planning, (2) sexual and reproductive health and rights, and (3) population issues, in the developing world.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833648","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-06","<p>Hate crime of any kind, directed against any community, race or religion has absolutely no place in our society. Action Against Hate, the UK Government's Plan for tackling hate crime sets out how the Government will tackle this divisive crime. We have given since 2011 £1.9 million to Tell MAMA to tackle anti-Muslim hatred and Islamophobia. Tell Mama also offers support to victims and works with the criminal justice agencies to bring perpetrators to justice. We also provide £85,000 to the StreetWise 'Stand UP' project which works in schools to tackle anti-Muslim hatred and anti-Semitism.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-02-06T13:50:40.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833648/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833648/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-30","Religious Hatred: Islam","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the announcement by the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government on 22 January (HC Deb, col 18), that they are giving £144,000 of support jointly to the Holocaust Educational Trust and the Union of Jewish Students to tackle anti-Semitism, prejudice and intolerance on university campuses, how much money they are allocating, if any, to Muslim groups in the UK for tackling Islamophobia.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833649","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-13","<p>​We have not made a specific assessment of this issue. The UK remains a leading donor to the Palestinian Authority and a strong supporter of its state-building efforts. As such we do not intend to provide support to proposals for a new Palestinian leadership. We remain committed to supporting a two-state solution as the only way to resolve the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, and encourage both parties to return to negotiations on this basis.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-02-13T17:02:07.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833649/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833649/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Palestinians: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment have they made of the Popular Conference of Palestinians Abroad, held in Istanbul in February 2017, which proposed a new national strategy for the Palestinians; and what support they intend to give to proposals for a new national leadership.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833650","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-13","<p>Whilst we have not raised this specific issue with the Israeli Government, we regularly discuss matters concerning the treatment of Palestinian minors in detention with the Israeli authorities.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-02-13T15:23:56.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833650/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833650/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel regarding the sentencing by an Israeli court of five boys from Hares to 15 years imprisonment for throwing stones.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833651","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-07","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) is forecasting sales receipts for surplus service family accommodation in the range of £1.75 - £2 million in 2018-19.</p><p>No other sales are currently programmed for subsequent years.</p><p>As part of the 1996 sale and leaseback arrangement with Annington Property Ltd, the MOD negotiated a 58% discount against market rent. A rent review is due with Annington Property Ltd in 2021.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2018-02-07T17:23:24.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833651/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833651/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Annington Homes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what savings the Ministry of Defence expected to make out of sales of unwanted service housing and reduction in rent negotiated with Annington Property Ltd for the financial years (1) 2018–19, (2) 2019–20, and (3) 2020–21.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL5265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833652","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-06","<p>To mark the centenary of the raid on Zeebrugge, the Royal Navy will be supporting two commemorative events in Belgium and Dover in April 2018.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2018-02-06T17:10:44.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833652/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833652/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","World War I: Anniversaries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans, if any, they have to commemorate the centenary of the raid on Zeebrugge on 23 April 1918.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL5266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833687","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>Currently there are 719 non-European Economic Area national general practitioner trainees working under a Tier 2 visa. On the completion of training, these trainees would be eligible to apply for indefinite leave to remain if they meet the requirements as set out by UK Visas and Immigration. Eligibility is based on individual circumstance and will be decided by UK Visas and Immigration.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-07T13:57:36.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833687/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833687/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","General Practitioners: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the number of non-EU GP registrars who are currently on GP training schemes in England who will not be eligible for indefinite leave to remain when they finish their three-year training.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","125446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833688","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>The Ministry of Justice collects data on the number of post mortem examinations commissioned by coroners and this is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/coroners-statistics-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/coroners-statistics-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>We have no plans to collect data on waiting times for coroner post mortems.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-02-07T14:03:09.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833688/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833688/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Post-mortems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to collect centrally data on waiting times for coronial post mortems for (a) adults, (b) children and (c) neonatal deaths.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","125447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833689","Home Office","false","2018-02-06","<p>There are no plans to review the safe return review policy.</p><p>Those who need protection are normally granted 5 years’ limited leave after which they are able to apply for permanent settlement. This policy has been in place since 2005 when automatic settlement for refugees was abolished.</p><p>All settlement applications are carefully considered on their individual merits and whilst we have always been clear that protection will be grated for as long as it is needed, we will assess whether there have been significant changes in country conditions or personal circumstances, which means that an individual no longer needs our protection.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-06T16:26:23.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833689/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833689/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-30","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will review her Department’s policy guidance on safe return reviews for refugees applying for settlement.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","125448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833690","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-06","<p>Ofgem’s assessment of regional differences in network charges, which was published in October 2015, concluded that there is no concentration of vulnerable consumers in any one particular distribution network region. Nonetheless, the Government recognises that electricity distribution costs are higher for the North of Scotland than any other region, and that is why the Hydro Benefit Replacement Scheme is providing an assistance amount of £59m in 2017/18 to reduce distribution charges there. The Government reviews this scheme every three years, in line with a statutory requirement.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-06T10:16:53.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833690/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833690/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Energy: Highlands of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect on energy consumers in the Highlands of charges relating to distribution network operations being applied to energy companies.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","125449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833691","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Cutting Red Tape Programme ran from 2015 – 2016 and published six sector based reviews of regulations. There have been no new Cutting Red Tape reviews since 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The published reports presented a series of findings to the responsible policy Departments who then worked with their stakeholders and regulators to address those findings and implement any changes. The Government is currently considering its approach to regulatory reform in the current Parliament.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-02-05T16:37:36.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833691/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833691/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress has been made on the Cutting Red Tape programme since 2015.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","125450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833692","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-02-07","<p>Publicly-funded superfast broadband projects under the Superfast Broadband Programme are subject to a competitive procurement process which is managed by the lead local authority. The successful supplier is selected by the local authority by determining which one has provided the most economically advantageous tender, using evaluation criteria which include cost and service quality parameters. The quality parameters can include consideration of the range of retail internet service providers who will offer retail services over the network. Broadband Delivery UK (BDUK) in DCMS provides assurance that the selected supplier’s solution meets EU state aid requirements and that there is no over-compensation of the supplier.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-02-07T13:34:02.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833692/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833692/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-30","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that funding for superfast broadband solutions have public support.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","125451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833693","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>Information relating to the revenue funding allocations made to Swindon Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) are provided in the following table. Figures are not directly comparable between primary care trusts (PCTs) and CCGs due to changes in geographic cover and commissioning responsibilities.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>National Health Service Body</p></td><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total Revenue Allocation £000’s</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Swindon PCT<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>294,545</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>315,703</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>325,407</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Swindon CCG<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>219,930</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>228,966</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>247,013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>257,364</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2017-18<sup>5</sup></p></td><td><p>293,574</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><sup> </sup></p><p>Notes:</p><p><sup>1</sup>As a result of the Health and Social Care Act 2012, Swindon PCT ceased to exist as at 31 March 2013 and the commissioning functions of the PCT passed to various organisations (NHS England became responsible for: primary care contracts, secondary care dental, military health, some public health functions and specialist commissioning contracts).</p><p><sup>2</sup>Swindon CCG allocations from 2013/14 onwards only include Core Allocations.</p><p>2015/16 CCG allocations include mid-year adjustments.</p><p>2017/18 allocations are as published in 2016 and do not include any subsequent adjustments.</p><p><sup>5</sup>Swindon CCG became delegated for Primary Care Medical from 1 April 2017, so the Primary Care Medical allocation has been included in the core allocation for 2017/18.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-02-07T13:50:32.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833693/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833693/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Health Services: Swindon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much money from the public purse has been available for the provision of NHS services in Swindon in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","125452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833694","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-07","<p>The British Government is concerned by recent clashes along the internal border between Somali Regional State and Oromia, especially where this has led to loss of life, displacement, or delayed the delivery of humanitarian assistance in response to drought. In recent bilateral dialogues with the Ethiopian Government, we have reinforced the need for all actors to resolve grievances peacefully rather than through violence, and for all security forces to exercise restraint. We continue to monitor the situation closely.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-02-07T17:15:43.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833694/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833694/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Ethiopia: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to help bring about a peaceful resolution to the recent unrest in Ethiopia.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","125453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833695","Home Office","false","2018-02-02","<p>The information is not held centrally and to obtain it would exceed the disproportionate cost threshold.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-02-02T10:52:55.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833695/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833695/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-30","Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average timescale has been for a person to be released under investigation by the police since the implementation of the Policing and Crime Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","125454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833696","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>Court reform is designed to improve our courts, which includes people’s ability to access justice. Various suppliers are enabling the department to deliver against our court reform goals, and contractual arrangements are in place to ensure they deliver our requirements.</p><p>The PwC arrangement does not include any prima facie assessment of performance related to access to justice. There are other performance related measures applied to that contract to enable PwC support the department.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-02-07T17:52:10.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833696/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833696/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Courts: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether access to justice will be used as a criteria by his Department to assess the performance of (a) PwC and (b) other contractors in the delivery of digital courts reform contracts.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833697","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>NHS Improvement, working with NHS England and key stakeholders, have produced a series of publications and learning events supporting trusts to ensure good patient flow in acute care. This includes ‘Good Practice Guide: Focus on Improving Patient Flow’<sup>1</sup> and a series of national conferences on patient flow and streaming delivered by Emergency Care Improvement Partnership.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England and NHS Improvement are also jointly leading work to ensure that patients are appropriately triaged at their first point of contact with the National Health Service to ensure that they are treated in the most appropriate healthcare setting. This includes primary care streaming for people attending accident and emergency and triage services for patients being referred by their general practitioner for planned hospital care where there are community health services available to provide their treatment.</p><p> </p><p>Note:</p><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup><a href="https://improvement.nhs.uk/resources/good-practice-guide-focus-on-improving-patient-flow/" target="_blank">https://improvement.nhs.uk/resources/good-practice-guide-focus-on-improving-patient-flow/</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-02-07T13:45:42.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833697/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833697/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to share best practice in providing triage services for patients among hospital trusts.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","125456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833698","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-06","<p>a) Estimates of the residential planning applications granted (planning approvals) for England and in each local authority district, year to September quarter 2017, are shown in table P136 at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-planning-application-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-planning-application-statistics</a></p><p>Earlier versions of table P136 are also available from the same link:</p><ul><li><p>those for years ending July 2012 to June 2017 are under the heading, “Historical Live Tables”, and</p></li><li><p>those for years ending September 2010 to June 2012 are available from the relevant link to the National Archives.</p></li></ul><p>b) Estimates of house building; new build dwellings completions for England and in each local authority district, to September quarter 2017, are shown in Live Table 253a at the following link.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-house-building" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-house-building</a></p><p>These cover new build dwellings only and should be regarded as a leading indicator of overall housing supply. The Department also publishes an annual release entitled ‘Housing supply: net additional dwellings, England’, which is the primary and most comprehensive measure of housing supply.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-02-06T16:06:59.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833698/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833698/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-30","Housing: Swindon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many (a) new build planning approvals and (b) houses built there were in Swindon in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","125457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833699","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-07","<p>The Government has no plans to commence provisions in Part 6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 relating to moving traffic enforcement powers. Other provisions relating to civil parking enforcement have already been commenced.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-02-07T15:17:31.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833699/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833699/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-30","Traffic Management Act 2004","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will commence Part 6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","125458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833700","Department for Education","false","2018-02-07","<p>The department published revised guidance for schools on the use of the physical education and sport premium in October 2017. This revised guidance can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/pe-and-sport-premium-for-primary-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/pe-and-sport-premium-for-primary-schools</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-02-07T17:39:08.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833700/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833700/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-30","Schools: Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to provide guidance on how the sport premium can be used in schools.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","125459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833701","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-06","<p>The Secretary of State for Work and Pensions talks regularly with the Secretary of State for Education, and the Secretary of State for Business, Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy, but has not yet had any formal discussions about identifying and filling the skills gaps in the labour market.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-02-06T12:03:48.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833701/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833701/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-30","Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Education and Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy on (a) identifying and (b) filling skills gaps in the labour market.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","125460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833702","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-06","<p>The Government undertook a review of the Feed-in Tariff scheme in 2015. In 2016 revised tariffs were published, out to the end of March 2019. We have no plans to review these tariffs.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-06T12:55:36.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833702/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833702/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Solar Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has plans to re-evaluate the feed-in tariff for households with solar panels with an energy performance certificate of band C and lower.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","125461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833703","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-06","<p>The Government undertook a review of the Feed-in Tariff scheme in 2015. In 2016 revised tariffs were published, out to the end of March 2019. We have no plans to review these tariffs.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-06T12:54:18.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833703/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833703/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Solar Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to vary the feed-in tariff for households with solar panels.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","125462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833704","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-07","<p>The UK supports the protection and improvement of human rights in Afghanistan through a number of bilateral and multilateral channels. We work with the National Unity Government, NGOs, and civil society in Afghanistan, as well as with the EU and international partners to support civil society, freedom of expression and the rights of women. The UK's commitment to the promotion of human rights in Afghanistan will continue after we have left the EU.</p><p> </p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-02-07T16:59:28.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833704/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833704/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Afghanistan: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government will take to promote human rights in Afghanistan once the UK has left the (a) EU and (b) EU+ Local strategy.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","125463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833705","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-07","<p>The General Anti-Abuse Rule (GAAR) penalty applies to tax arrangements entered into on or after 15 September 2016. Before a GAAR penalty can be charged, HMRC must first enquire into tax returns once they are received and gather all relevant facts. For example, for income tax, arrangements to which a GAAR penalty may apply can first feature in tax returns in the year ended 5 April 2017, which must be filed with HMRC by 31 January 2018.</p><p>Whilst no penalties have been charged to date, HMRC is actively using the GAAR and in all cases referred to the GAAR Advisory Panel to date, the panel have agreed with HMRC, and been of the opinion that the cases should be pursued for GAAR counteraction. GAAR Panel decisions are published online at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-avoidance-general-anti-abuse-rule-gaar</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-02-07T15:33:53.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833705/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833705/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-30","Tax Avoidance: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on tax avoidance, how many penalties were imposed under the General Anti-Abuse Rule regarding (a) income tax and (b) corporation tax in each in (i) 2016 and (ii) 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","125464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833706","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-02-07","<p>Our aim is to ensure continuity during the implementation period, with international partners and the EU, and certainty for businesses and individuals.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>As such, our existing international agreements should continue to apply during the proposed time-limited implementation period.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>This includes the EEA Agreement and other important agreements which govern crucial elements of our trading and non-trading relationship with the three EEA EFTA states - Norway, Iceland and Liechtenstein.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Once the implementation period ends, we will no longer participate in the EU's international agreements. We will instead seek to put in place new arrangements to maintain our relationships with these countries.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-02-07T17:48:54.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833706/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833706/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-01-30","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether the Government's negotiating position is that the provisions of any implementation agreement will extend to the countries within the EEA.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","125465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833707","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-07","<p>​We are concerned about terrorist attacks in Egypt that have targeted the Coptic community and about reports of sectarian violence. Following the attacks last year, the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead, wrote to the President of Egypt to express her deep condolences and reiterate the UK's support for Egypt in its fight against terrorism. Combating sectarian violence is a shared strategic objective for the Egyptian and UK Governments and we welcome President Sisi's calls for peaceful coexistence between communities. The Egyptian Constitution contains protection for Freedom of Religious Belief. It is important that these rights are respected.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-07T17:17:47.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833707/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833707/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Egypt: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the Government of Egypt on the persecution of Christians and other minority faiths in Egypt.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","125466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833708","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Government regularly engages with energy suppliers and Meter Asset Providers (MAPs) to better understand the contractual developments in the marketplace for energy meters.</p><p>Deemed rental charges have been in use for a number of years and were introduced as an option for energy suppliers who did not want to sign a formal churn contract with the MAP.</p><p>Energy suppliers continue to have a choice of rental agreement when they gain a meter and the Government remain of the view that the current market is operating in a competitive way.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-05T15:26:41.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833708/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833708/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833708/answer/previousversion/39108","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to reduce the high deemed rental costs associated with contracts between meter asset providers and energy suppliers, particularly when a customer switches energy supplier.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","125467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833709","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Government publishes quarterly reports on the number of smart electricity and gas meters installed in Great Britain as part of its Smart Meters statistics collection: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/smart-meters-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/smart-meters-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p><p>As of 30 September 2017, there were 3.34 million smart and advanced gas meters operating across homes and businesses in Great Britain by large energy suppliers.</p><p> </p><p>Industry information shows there are now around 450 gas and electricity SMETS2 meters connected to the DCC system. Most of these are being operated in test conditions and around 80 have been installed in the live environment.</p><p> </p><p>Energy suppliers are continuing to test their systems ahead of a controlled ramp up on SMETS2 meters in the coming months.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-05T15:04:11.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833709/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833709/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833709/answer/previousversion/39110","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many (a) SMETS1 and (b) SMETS2 gas meters have been installed under the smart meters roll-out programme.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","125468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833710","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>Smart meter installation costs in the 2016 Cost-Benefit Analysis update reflect both energy suppliers’ latest actual data and their own forecasts of how installation costs would evolve over time.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-05T15:05:34.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833710/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833710/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833710/answer/previousversion/39113","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether smart meter installation costs have increased from the time when the 2016 cost-benefit analysis was conducted.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","125469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833711","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that every home and small business are offered smart meters by the end of 2020. The programme is making good progress and more than 8.6 million smart and advanced meters are operating in Great Britain, as of 30 September 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Energy suppliers are responsible for planning and delivering the roll-out of smart meters, working within the legal framework established by the Government. Energy suppliers’ licence conditions require them to take ‘all reasonable steps’ to roll-out smart meters to all their domestic and small business customers by 31 December 2020. Ofgem is responsible for regulating energy suppliers against this obligation.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-05T15:05:52.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833711/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833711/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833711/answer/previousversion/39115","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate has he made of the number of smart meters that will be installed under the smart meter roll-out programme by 2020.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","125470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833712","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-02-07","<p>According to VisitBritain, over a third of visitors to the UK are drawn to locations which have been used in films and TV series.</p><p> </p><p>In Northern Ireland, the television series Game of Thrones has been a great draw, encouraging visitors to locations such as Giant’s Causeway and the Dark Hedge.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2018-02-07T16:10:36.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833712/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833712/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-30","Arts: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment he has made of the contribution of the growth in the creative industries in Northern Ireland to UK-wide tourism.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","125471"
